# Auth discipline

The dashboard uses **NextAuth v5 (Auth.js) with Microsoft Entra ID
(Azure AD)**. Wiring lives at the project root (`auth.ts`) per Auth.js
convention; the dashboard-facing helpers live at `lib/auth.ts`.

## Hard rules

- **Every Server Component / Server Action that reads program data MUST
  call `requireUser()` from `lib/auth.ts`.** The proxy already redirects
  unauthenticated requests, but Server Functions are NOT in the proxy
  chain in Next 16 (see `node_modules/next/dist/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/03-file-conventions/proxy.md`),
  so a refactor that turns a Server Component into a Server Action can
  silently drop coverage.

- **Privileged actions (writes, exports of sensitive data) MUST go
  through `requireRole(["ADMIN", "FINOPS", ...])`.** v0.2 has no writes
  yet; the helper is in place so v0.3 PRs that add them have no excuse.

- **Never read `process.env.AZURE_AD_*` directly from a page or
  component.** Those values are consumed only by `auth.ts` (NextAuth
  wiring) and `lib/integrations/azuread/real.ts` (Microsoft Graph
  client). Anywhere else is a leak vector.

- **Never widen the proxy matcher to allow unauth routes** without
  explicit sign-off from a maintainer. The current matcher excludes only
  static assets; auth gating is handled by the `authorized` callback in
  `auth.ts`, which lets `/api/auth/*` through itself.

- **Do not bypass auth in tests.** If a test needs a session, mock
  `lib/auth.ts` (`getCurrentUser` / `requireUser`) at the import level.
  Don't add `SKIP_AUTH=1` style env-var bypasses — strict-mode was a
  deliberate choice (per scoping §4 integration #1 + AGENTS.md §0).

## Role mapping

`roleFromClaims()` in `lib/auth-roles.ts` is pure and unit-tested. The
production rule is "AAD `groups` claim wins; email patterns are a
sandbox bridge until real groups exist". When the tenant has real
groups:

1. Configure the AAD app reg's "Token configuration" to include
   `groupMembershipClaims=SecurityGroup`.
2. Populate `GROUP_ROLE_MAP` in `lib/auth-roles.ts` with the real group
   object IDs.
3. Trim `EMAIL_ROLE_RULES` to an empty array (or keep one fallback for
   break-glass admins).
4. Update tests in `lib/auth-roles.test.ts`.

## When extending

- Adding a new provider (e.g. SAML for an external partner) → add it to
  the `providers` array in `auth.ts`, NOT in lib/. Keep all NextAuth
  config in one file so a security review touches one place.
- Adding new session fields (e.g. tenantId) → extend the `jwt` and
  `session` callbacks in `auth.ts`, then update `SessionUser` in
  `lib/auth.ts`. Roles + email + name are the only fields needed by
  v0.2 surfaces.
